,Recommended,220200,7931207,"Posted: 5 December, 2013",all,Haggis,"Kerbal Space Program basically sums up the entire reason as to why I wish I were an astronaut/rocket scientist, and the entire reason as to why there is no way in hell I could ever be one.The game has two modes (as of the time of this writing), Career, and Sandbox.  Sandbox is exactly what it sounds like, minus the cat poop and the lost action figures (never forget you little Anakin!).  In sandbox, you build a rocket ship or a space plane, and you go to space.  Half of the time...  The other half is spent trying to figure out why in the hell did that stage not properly go off, only to realize you didn't actually attach your rockets to that stage...  But anyways, sandbox mode is the mode you play when you want to make a giant ship in a few minutes and fly it into the sun.  Because why?  Because Science!The second mode, Career, is basically ""Here's a couple of pieces, those guys over there are the pilots, see if we can't get this into space.""  The beginning parts are spent mindlessly launching rockets into the ground because you have no idea what you are doing, and when you finally figure out what you're doing, you can have some fun.  In Career, you gain science points for everything you do.  Like, everything...  Such as EVAing a Kerbal while you're still launching, dropping a mysterious goo on the ground, into the water, into space, into orbit, and pretty much anywhere you can drop that goo, you'll get science for it.  You can get science for successful missions, unsuccessful missions, missions that you didn't think could go wrong but did, missions you thought would never be possible but was because who needs logic.This is definitely one of my new favorite games out there.  Although, as much as I'd hate to admit it, this game is MUCH better being played on a controller (or joystick, which is awesome if you can), just because the little fine tuning you have to do can be a pain when using your keyboard.The only complaint I have is that I freaking got Jeb stuck into orbit with no jetpack fuel in Career mode, and he isn't even in the ship anymore, and so the only way I could save him is by very, VERY precise calculations, that I'm too lazy to do and end up just winging it.  I mean, I could just terminate him and he'll respawn eventually, but it's FREAKING JEB!  I CAN'T KILL JEB!So anyways, I hope you found this review helpful, and I would ABSOLUTELY recommend this game to people.  But, I suggest packing enough fuel to get out of orbit, or wait until you have docking ports...  Then you won't end up with Jeb stuck in space..."
,Recommended,220200,9276040,"Posted: 26 February, 2014",all,Cheddar,How hard could it be? It's only rocket science. If the idea of putting parts to build various flying machines in appealing you you I highly recommend you try this out. It's a got a bit of learning curve but it is worth it. To make things easier on yourself you can skip the in-game tutorials (they mostly confused me) and hop on YouTube instead. Scott Manley has a good tutorial series. This is the link for the playlist:https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLYu7z3I8tdEmqpOkQZCl5SZB5t0vXuxE0You'll probably want to at least make some attempts at flying prior to jumping to the videos as a lot of the fun of the game can come from failure and cool explosions... not that you'll have a shortage of those later. Rescue missions on distant worlds make for some amusing challenges.
,Recommended,220200,22903415,"Posted: 10 May, 2016",all,XxPieIsTastyxX,"My favorite game. There's so much to do, and so many places to go. A wholeworldsolar system of freedom and opportunity awaits!You can play in sandbox, science mode, or career mode. In sandbox mode, you have unlimited funds, and everything is unlocked. In science mode, you have infinite funds, but you need to unlock things with science. In career mode, you have limited funds and science, as well as reputation. You must accept contracts from companies to fund your space program, and progress through the tech tree.The game has in-depth tutorials and a guide, as well as different scenarios to try out. The community around the game is great, and Squad (the company that makes KSP) is great. I have seen them implement many things the community asks for, and even bring modders on to the team to help.Speaking of mods, there exists a plethora to choose from. Whether you want to make your game easier, harder, better looking, more realistic, or crazy, there is a mod for you. They include things from graphics overhauls to aerodynamic overhauls to vast quantities of new parts to autopilot systems you code yourself.The game is both simple and challenging at the same time. It's easy enough to build a rocket, but can you make it fly? Can you get into orbit? How about to theMoonMun? What aboutMarsDuna? The answers may be no at first, but you learn. You slowly understad more and more, and after playing the game for a while, the answer becomes yes. And in that moment, you realize: ""Hey! I know how space works! This is orbital mechanics! And I know how to do it!"" It gives you a wondrous feeling of accomplishment, each time you do something new. That feeling barely fades, as I still feel my heart swell a little every time I land on the Mun.So go ahead, give the game a shot. It may seem daunting, but it's really quite fun -- and deceptively simple.How hard can rocket science be anyway?"
