,Recommended,220200,7768592,"Posted: 26 November, 2013",all,calderracrusade,"If you don't know anything about the space program or orbit maneuvers, this is a hilariously fun game of attempting to build rockets and often causing massive explosions while your cute little green pilots scream on in horror (except for Jebediah, who is cheering all the way). Laugh at your new build, where you've strapped on dozens of boosters, and be rolling on the floor during launch as you watch everything slowly (or, quickly) fall apart.If you know vaguely of the space program and think learning something about how to get things into space will be fun, this is a science kit in a box. Have all the fun above, plus you'll learn what ""freefall"" and ""orbit"" and ""retrograde"" really mean with hands-on experience. Relive the Apollo missions to the moon (or for Kerbals, the Mun), simulate real NASA missions (or try to and learn much as you stay up all night trying to make your rocket fly correctly). Addictive, cute, and fun.If you've mastered space docking and other-world-landing in other games, you'll still appreciate the excellent physics and the cute take on what is often a difficult genre to break into. The physics are all there and are quite good- you could teach a class using many of the features even in this early beta. With community mods, the physics get even better (or crazier, as you wish). Fans have even programmed automated burn correction programs so you can do a professional job. Calculate delta-vee and puzzle as your probe lands precisely where it was supposed to based on your mathematical calculations- in a game featuring cute bobble-headed green men."
