,Recommended,220200,15635747,"Posted: 1 May, 2015",all,Celador,"I've been waiting patiently before reviewing this game and finally they released it so i can post my thoughts about it.The idea behind this game is amazing - you get to explore a solar system, build various rockets, pretend to be an engineer, a pilot or an explorer. They've managed to allow as much creativity as it actually possible at this current development level for simulation/strategy game.HOWEVER (it is a big however, i know) before you can actually enjoy anything like building a satellite to orbit around some distant planet, or a two way mission to the Mun - you will either have to learn hours and hours, and hours, and hours, even more hours of youtube tutorials or... cheat.When it comes to tutorials and explaining ""how things work in the game we made"" the developers failed so miserably, so utterly and completely, that you actually have to wonder which audience they intended this game for?Telling a new player to try and land a vehicle near space center - is not a tutorial. Forgetting to mention recently added features like heating and cooling, so they would inevitably burn in the atmosphere is a shocking oversight. Not mentioning how to save up fuel when launching vessels, changing orbits or de-orbiting is just lousy.Bottom line is - there is no comprehensive tutorial in this game whatsoever, no learning curve, no actually useful in game tips, tooltips or explanations on anything. Period.So before you actually can enjoy this game in its fullest (repetitively launching badly designed pieces of crap is just a part of it) - you will have to spend hours learning how the hell you can launch a vessel properly, save fuel, dock, transfer to another object, land, land in different atmosphere, land without an atmosphere, take off, etc. etc. etc.I was expecting them to completely revamp the tutorials and the learning curve - they did not. Because of that i was prepared to thumb it down but i could not. Even though developers clearly do not care about players actually getting into their game and enjoying it without wasting a lot of time - modders do care. There are mods that allow cheating, better parts and complete designs which reduce the difficulty curve significantly. There are also plenty of videos (i recommend Scott Manley) which explain various game aspects in details and manage to be both interesting and educational at the same time.So yeah... while i am very disappointed in developers, the community and modders made this game better, good enough to recommend it."
