76561198018345517,Recommended,220200,9659040,"Posted: 28 March, 2014",all,Kenshusei Richard,"Kerbal space program is by far the most interesting game I’ve played in a long time. In this engaging game, you are given control of a budding space agency and a pre set solar system for you to explore. You get to design, build, launch and pilot rockets and planes in a realistic space flight simulator and discover just how hard space missions can actually be. As of today (29.03.14) there are no objectives or mission in the campaign mode yet, but that hasn’t stopped me from clocking in over 200 enjoyable hours since release.As the game is still in development, there is also tons more material to follow and each time I am left really excited by playing and even more excited to hear news of updates, which are quite frequent to give the devs at Squad credit, ranging from three to four months between updates typically. The game has tons of features and is expanding all the time- from figuring out how to launch ever increasing payloads into orbit, to conducting specific experiments in space to basic exploration. You even have to plan in for survival in space by building batteries and solar panels to your ships as without power, they become dead sticks in space. For any science geek like myself or for anyone who is interested in the space programs of the world in general, this game is a must have and is worth every penny of its £20 asking price in my opinion.Kerbal also gives you a massive sense of achievement as you learn more about the physics of flying space missions.  I still have vivid memories and even a grin while thinking about my very first successful landing on the Mun, the nearest orbiting body to the home planet.After playing for over 200 hours I can thankfully report that there is  still a huge mass of things for me to do. I’ve still not found a way to explore some of the further most planets- my rocket designs are simply not up to that task yet which is another motivation for me to keep playing. I’ve still not been able to return a man (kerbal) from another planet yet despite several drone and probe landings. All of this, plus the additional updates means that I can play this game after a long day at work knowing that I’ve still only really scratched the surface.Kerbal at present has 2 modes. There is the sandbox in which you get all the parts to go play with instantly- and there is the skeleton of the Career mode which is fleshed out more in updates along the road. In the career mode, you unlock parts for your space program using a resource called science. Science is generated by doing experiments from certain locations E.G. a crew report whilst flying over some mountains. The game has a great mechanic built in; in which running repeat experiments on the same thing has huge diminishing returns. This means that if you want to generate more science and unlock more parts, your missions need to go further and do something new. You also come across a problem- Science can only be collected on Kerbin, your home planet. So how do you get your experimental results back home? Do you plan for a return trip and build a larger craft with more fuel and re-entry kit or will you sacrifice some of the “science” you could have earned by using the radio to transmit data back to Kerbin- which means you’ll have to go back and do the experiment again to get the rest of the science you could have earned? These kinds of decisions really colour the choices you make,  challenge a player to put time and effort into their designs and to think about their flight plan as with limited fuel and power, missions are not straightforward. For those who don’t like that idea, relax- there is a debug mode in which you can grant yourself infinite fuel so you can look around everything with a little ship- but where is the fun in that?The moding community for kerbal space program is fantastic. It’s a little harder to integrate mods into the campaign mode, but it can be done even by my severely limited computing skills. As for the sandbox, moding is fun and adds new features and challenges. Want to map planets from orbit? There’s a mod for that. Want to include life support like oxygen/ CO2? There is a mod for that too- hell there is even a radio chatter mod. Pretty much any feature you would like to have will most likely have a mod for it and most of them can be found at the Kerbal space port (Google it, easy to find). The community input into kerbal is phenomenal allowing you to have sci-fi fantasy engines that can fly you out of the solar system on one tank of fuel or delicate life support/ power features for more realistic missions. Another mod I would like to sing the praises of is Kerbal space program multiplayer. Here you can fly missions with other users over the net. Hell yes! But I can’t promise that this will be sticking around as the game engine updates frequently. So if you’re thinking of buying for that reason- wait; as of yet there is not official multiplayer of the game.Lastly- are there any issues? Well yes, this is a work in progress after all. Some of the larger rockets can wobble strangely and some of the connectors can have issues, meaning that the complicated craft you spend 2 hours designing needs to be tweaked repeatedly.One of the parts in the core game causes an error as of last update (the hitchhiker support module) but I’m sure this can be and will be fixed- and it's not a majorly inportant part anyhow. But other than these minor teething problems, which to be fair can be expected of a game in development, there are no major issues that I have found or that I can think of that are really frustrating.If you need any more information before deciding whether this game is for you, check out YouTube- there are hundreds of vids up there with commentary and good examples of game play. Hope this review was helpful in making your choice."
