76561198263926402,Recommended,220200,32455947,Posted: 15 June,all,guitarman152,"Right, firstly take no notice what so ever of the recent reduction to 'very positive' on the review rating. That's because KSP was just bought by a new company (you will probably see about it in other reviews) and everybodies giving poor reviews based on speculations about what this company may or may not do in the future...Now to point. KSPdoes notdeserve this mark down. I personally think it is the best game I have ever bought!Yes it is £30. I avoided it for far too long because of this. Then I tried the demo, granted it was uber outdated but I knew that and was hooked anyway. It's not available at the time of writing due to maintanace. I assume the devs are updateing it to be closer to the current state. However, I have gotten much more than my money's worth. 111hrs at the moment and rising doesn't include the countless hours loooking at tutorials, researching calculations, planning, learning more of the real world physics. If you let it the scope of enjoyment can be huge!The graphics, whilst not next gen, are pleasant (imho) and with mods beautiful. Yet, you can still run KSP solidly on a toaster like mine.The gameplay is fun, varied and involving. You can play away to your hearts content. You can build your craft for hours with precision, you can fly your creations around the kerbol system ventureing to many different planets and moons. And you can forget something and watch the fireworks before redesigning to eliminate the fault.But, what if I want to fly around but can't stand building? You can download others awesome ships from the forums to fly if you wish. Or inversly make your own ships and let others fly them.There's plenty to do here. Ingame world acheivements keep you busy (ie makeing it into space or getting into orbit of a certain planet for the first time), as well as ingame contract missions (for money profit and science!!) or your own set goals.On top of all this it can be hilarious watching your little kerbals bounce down a hill on Minmus (Kerbin's (Earth) second tiny moon) ragdolling in the low gravity.Oh yeah, and you dont just have to build rockets, planes are available. Or go further and make a 'spaceplane'!Plus the modding community is huge, active and awesome! And can add hours to your playtime.If you love physics, you'll love KSP. If you love space sandboxes, you'll love KSP. If you love flight sims, you'll love KSP.The learning curve is steep. But not insurmountable.KSP doesn't deserve this down marking due to politics around which compant owns it. It is a solid, engaging and imensly fun game... Do yourself a favour and get it, you'll see what I mean.Edit: Just seen it's on sale for £14.99. If you like the sound of KSP or are teetering on the edge this is an insane bargin. Just buy it now!!"
