,Recommended,220200,9639689,"Posted: 26 March, 2014",all,SpacemanMitch,"This game is beyond amazing. It does have a sizable learning curve (nobody ever gets into orbit on their first try), but once you get the hang of it (and you will, given you have enough patience), it's dangerously addicting. There's just so much to do in this game that you'll never run out of things to do. Even if, by some rediculously low chance, you get bored with the game or run out of things to do, there's a massive mod community that can in some cases outshine the vanilla game itself. There's 14 celestial bodies to land on (not counting the sun [kerbol], kerbin [home planet], or jool [gas giant with no tangible surface]), ranging in difficulty from the captured asteroid moon of gilly (the gravity is so low that your EVA jet pack can get you not only to orbit, but ALL THE WAY BACK TO KERBIN), to the massive purple planet of Eve (its pea-soup thick atmosphere and crushing gravity make getting to orbit from sea level a challenge that seperates the space tourist casuals from the highly skilled elite veterans). You can launch into orbit, build space stations, visit other worlds, build bases, even escape the grasp of the sun and go interstellar. Your imagination (and to some extent, your patience) are quite literally your only limits in this game."
