,Recommended,220200,9703958,"Posted: 2 April, 2014",all,grampa Wilbur,bestest
,Recommended,220200,9719648,"Posted: 3 April, 2014",all,GRockGames,"Oh, this game.  Where do I begin?Okay, let's start with the fact that this game is still under development, so while the game is awesome as it is, it can only get better from here.I remember when I bought Kerbal Space Program.  I had just seen a playthrough of it on Markiplier's YouTube channel back when he was under 600K subs.  This game looked so dang fun that I just couldn't not pick it up and play it.That was before I bought the game.......I got sucked into this game so much that for the first weeks, I couldn't set it down.  While on YouTube, most people usually put a ship on the Mun (The moon of Kerbin, the home planet of the Kerbals for which the game was named.  Yeah, those little green guys are called Kerbals) and then call it good and never really move on.  There is so much more to this game.  So let's begin with its gameplayGAMEPLAY:I'm going to say this right off the bat, this is not a Scribblenauts-style draw a cute little rocket ship and then it blasts off into space.  No, in Kerbal Space Program, you better have a space worthy, stable, powerful spacecraft, or you will crash and burn quick.  Structural integrity, engine heat, weight and thrust distribution all play into how successful your spacecraft will be.  Another major point is that, realistically and in KSP, Spaceships don't just go through hyperspace or go in any sort of straight line to other places.  You have to do this yourself.  This may sound complicated, but the next point is the learning curve.LEARNING CURVE:While the above may sound strikingly complex, it really isn't.  The tutorials for this game are fantastic, and if they aren't enough, there are plenty of beginner videos out there (The best are by Scott Manley on YouTube, whose sexy scottish voice leads you through the ins and outs of building a space-worthy ship).  From starting with a cockpit, parachute, and a solid rocket booster, to making twenty stage rocket ships to blast off to the furthest reaches of the solar system, this game is meant to be taken very slowly, so be patient and the rewards will come to you.  Not to mention the maneuver node system is the most useful thing on the planet.STORY:Who needs a story when little green men jump around 30 feet on the moon?  I think there's no need for such a thing.CONCLUSION:This game is an absolute necessity to complete any gamer's library.  It really is the only game of its kind, and no one should be afraid to pick this game up and give it a try.  You will fail, a lot.  I know I did.  But be patient, take the game slowly, and eventually you'll be landing on Eve without even trying.This game is absolutely worth the price it has, even in development.  Go and buy it.  Why are you reading this?  I have no idea what you're doing here, you should be playing this game."
,Recommended,220200,9719901,"Posted: 3 April, 2014",all,Neoprofin,"I want to be clear, I am absolutely terrible at this game and it in no way affects my enjoyment.I can barely get a ship out of the atmosphere some nights and I certainly can't accomplish all the wonderful complex things people seem to be doing on the internet. It's worth it though. The first time you put a manned modual in orbit around the planet and take your Kerbalnaut out on a space walk as the sun comes over the horizon there's just an incredible sense of calm. It makes me imagine the views of real astronauts staring down at the Earth as it slowly spins by.Also, failure is just as exciting as success. Watching your rocket develop a slight wobble that becomes a spin that becomes a 1000 mph explosive projectile hurtling into space is worth the price of the game. Imagine desperately jettesing your second stage rockets because they're imbalanced and then reaching outerspace only to realize you won't have enough rocket power  to complete your mission. Watch helplessly as three brave souls drift slowly out into space, alone and out of control."
