76561197995276300,Recommended,220200,7787657,"Posted: 27 November, 2013",all,dan.flaming,"(my computer: i5 2500K, 8GB RAM, AMD 6870, all stock speeds)The game is awesome, very much a sandbox in space!Game basics:Sandbox rocket building and flying. Make up your own mission and carry it out! Like: Land on the moon, sorry ""Mun"". Or build a space station. Or think big, like build a space station around Jupiter, ""Jool"" and land on all the moons!You will crash though, and often. And explode while launching, or drop engines full of fuel before having a chance to fire them. That is what makes a successful mission mean something!Is it a Simulator?The game is not quite perfect simulator, but is close. The scale of the planets and their orbits is quite a bit smaller than our Solar System, mostly to make it not take so long to do things. (KSP launch: ~5 min. NASA launch: ~15 min.) Also, the astronomical objects have ""sphere of influence"". This means that you will either be orbiting Kerbin, or the Mun (or on suborbital or escape trajectory), but never influenced by both at the same time. (This means no Lagrange points). Other than those two points the game feels very much like a good simulator. You can make a free return trajectory to the moon, use your landing module to land and return in the command capsule.It's not done!The game gets a new patch every few weeks, they add new things to the game. Recently added is a science component to career mode, where you unlock parts by ""doing science"" in different places. The sandbox mode is very playable. Though the unity engine used is 32 bit (?) that means that it can only make use of 4GB or RAM which can slow things down with large ships. To notice that though you pretty much have to be building large interplanetary, multi-mission ships.Who is this for?If you like space, engineering, problem solving, you will enjoy this game.Demo:I started with the demo. It's free, it includes some parts and Kerbin, Mun and Sun. It is very possible to land and return from the Mun in the demo. By then you should know if you like it."
