,Recommended,220200,13750754,"Posted: 31 December, 2014",all,Geomancer,"What a surprisingly fun game, but also an extreamly challenging one!Prepare to become a rocket scientist because in this sandbox game you are tasked with designing rockets and using them to conduct science around the solar system. For a game it is actually pretty darn educational to be honest because it teaches you the basics of the physics involved in interplanetary travel and orbits.It is still very much a work in progress, but the progress is far enough along that there is actually quite a lot you can do in the game. It's all pretty much open universe (haha, instead of open world, you get it.... okay I'll stop now) and a complete sandbox. The game does not give you direction on what to do. So because of that, you really need to be self motivated.There is a basic tutorial in the game, but it really isn't what I would call sufficient to really get you started. Prepare to spend a coule hours (yes hours) watching YouTube tutorials so you can figure out exactly how it is you get into orbit, how you change your orbit, and how you can land on other celestial bodies.There are three modes of gameplay currently. Career, Science, and Sandbox. Career mode is the closest to an objective based gameplay that you're going to get. But this is also the hardest mode to play in. You have to manage your budget, your reputation, and complete missions to keep going but those same missions (called contracts) can provide you concrete goals to set out to achieve.In Science you start out with only basic parts and must conduct science experiements to collect enough science points to unlock more parts (very much the same as in Career mode). The big difference is you don't have to worry about money or reputation at all.In Sandbox mode, as should be obvious, you get access to everything right away and can build away to your hearts content, and like Minecraft there are people out there who make absoulty amazing creations.I recommend playing Science when you're starting out because it will ease you into each spaceship part instead of hitting you with all of them right away.So if you're not the type of gamer who can dig into a game to figure out how it works star far away from this game. If failure after a 30 minute flight makes your blood boil and rage ... stay away from this game. It really requires patience, creativity, and critical thinking to do much more than get into orbit in this game."
