,Recommended,220200,7855959,"Posted: 30 November, 2013",all,Single Malt,"I was pleasantly surpised with Kerbal.If you think it would be awesome to build satellites, space stations, rovers, and landing on the moon in your very own custom built rocket that is more likely to explode than get you there, than this game is for you. They do a reasonable job adding physics principles (weight/drag, gravity, and operating in space) using a waypoint and thruster bursts system.I'd say that the rocket building editor is one of the finer parts of the game and the controls are generally intuitive.While there is a ""career mode"" this game is more about the open sandbox. The world (or space for that matter) is your oyster to explore.You might be tempted to read the online wiki for instructions on how to get into orbit and then out to the moon (Mun). I suggest forgoing such help until you really get stuck as figuring it out is have the fun of this game!My biggest grips are awkward camera angles, lack of a really good tutorial, and parts that seem unfinished (where it is in alpha so this is all entirely forgivable).One thing to note thought, this game is really cpu and ram intensive. This is particularly true when you make very large and complex rockets.I'd put this game in the ""casual gamer"" category. Its a great time waster with surprising depth, and you really get a sense of accomplishment after completing that landing..."
