,Recommended,220200,10530852,"Posted: 19 June, 2014",all,wucebillis,"Most games have a learning curve based around mastery of gameplay mechanics, improving reflexes and situational awareness, or problem solving. KSP is an altogether different beast: you'll need to learn orbital mechanics and some basic rocket science to succeed, but unlike most games, this knowledge is directly applicable to (and derived from) real life situations.Building rockets is hard. Getting rockets into space is harder. Landing your Kerbals on the Mun, visiting different planets, and bringing them back alive is a singular achievment. Yet KSP never makes the learning process tedious; miserable failures - usually explosive in nature - often elicit laughter and joy, and every mistake is an opportunity to learn something new.Despite being early access, KSP is remarkably polished, and each update adds meaningful, useful content. The developers are engaged with the community to a terrific extent and the community itself is among the best around. There are mods for just about everything, in case the core game ever starts to get stale.You can't go wrong with Kerbal Space Program. It's a wonderful, gorgeous game."
